      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What Is a Notice to Complete in a Queensland Property Contract?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A notice to complete is one of the most powerful tools a seller has when a buyer fails to settle. Understanding when to use it and what follows is critical.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Property settlements do not always go smoothly. Buyers can run into finance delays, personal complications, or in some cases simply change their mind after the cooling-off period has passed. When a buyer fails to settle on the due date, a Queensland seller has a specific legal mechanism available: the notice to complete. Understanding what this notice does, when it applies, and what it means for your sale is important for any vendor navigating a difficult settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a notice to complete actually is</h2>
      <p>A notice to complete is a formal written demand served by one party on the other requiring them to complete the contract within a specified timeframe. In Queensland residential property transactions, this notice is most commonly served by a seller on a buyer who has failed to settle on the agreed settlement date.</p>

      <p>The notice does not immediately end the contract. It gives the defaulting party a final window to perform their obligations. If they do not settle within that window, the issuing party gains the right to terminate the contract and pursue remedies.</p>

      <p>The standard REIQ residential contract used in most Queensland transactions provides a framework for notices to complete, but the specific mechanics depend on the version of the contract and any special conditions that have been negotiated. Your solicitor should be the one drafting and serving the notice, not your agent.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When can a seller issue a notice to complete?</h2>
      <p>A seller can issue a notice to complete when the buyer is in default. The most common default is failing to settle on the agreed settlement date. However, a buyer can also be in default earlier in the process if they fail to satisfy other contractual obligations, such as paying a deposit by the required date.</p>

      <p>It is important that the seller themselves is not in default at the time of issuing the notice. A seller who has not fulfilled their own obligations under the contract cannot validly issue a notice to complete against a buyer. This is one of the reasons why your solicitor must manage this process, not the agent. Getting the timing or the basis wrong can undermine your legal position.</p>

      <p>The notice must also be served correctly, typically in writing to the buyer or their solicitor in accordance with the contract's notice provisions. Informal communication from the agent to the buyer's agent is not a valid notice to complete.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The notice period: how long does the buyer get?</h2>
      <p>Under the standard REIQ contract, a notice to complete typically gives the defaulting party five business days to complete the transaction. This is not a negotiable period, and the five business day count begins from the day after the notice is served.</p>

      <p>Five business days is a meaningful window. In most cases, if a buyer is experiencing a short-term finance delay, this period gives them enough time to resolve the issue and settle. If the buyer is genuinely unable or unwilling to proceed, the notice period simply confirms what is already apparent.</p>

      <p>Some contracts may specify a different notice period through special conditions. If you are uncertain what notice period applies in your contract, your solicitor can advise you before issuing anything.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the buyer still does not settle?</h2>
      <p>If the buyer fails to settle within the notice period, the seller has the right to terminate the contract. Termination must be done formally, again in writing, and typically through your solicitor.</p>

      <p>On termination, the seller's primary remedy under the standard REIQ contract is to forfeit the deposit. This means the deposit held in trust, typically 10% of the purchase price, is paid to the seller. Forfeiting the deposit is a significant financial consequence for the buyer and provides the seller with some compensation for the failed settlement.</p>

      <p>Beyond the deposit, the seller may also have a claim for damages if the forfeited deposit does not fully cover the losses arising from the failed settlement. This is more complex and depends on what the property ultimately sells for and what costs were incurred. Your solicitor can advise on whether pursuing a damages claim is practical and worth the cost in your specific situation.</p>

      <p>After termination, the seller can re-list and sell the property to another buyer. The practical reality is that the failed settlement will add weeks to your timeline and may affect your own purchase plans if you are buying simultaneously.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Can a buyer issue a notice to complete against a seller?</h2>
      <p>Yes. The notice to complete mechanism is available to both parties. A buyer can issue a notice to complete if the seller fails to settle on the due date. If the seller does not comply within the notice period, the buyer can terminate the contract and have the deposit refunded, and may also have a claim for damages.</p>

      <p>In practice, a buyer issuing a notice to complete against a seller is less common than the reverse. Sellers who fail to settle are typically dealing with complications around vacant possession, a delayed purchase of their next property, or issues with the property itself. These situations require careful legal handling from both sides.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The role of your solicitor</h2>
      <p>Your solicitor manages the notice to complete process entirely. This is not something your real estate agent can do on your behalf, and it is not something you should attempt to do yourself without legal advice. The legal requirements for a valid notice are specific, and a notice that is incorrectly drafted, served to the wrong party, or issued at the wrong time can be legally ineffective or worse, can expose you to claims.</p>

      <p>If settlement is approaching and there are signs the buyer may not be ready, contact your solicitor early. Early contact gives you more options. Your solicitor can communicate with the buyer's solicitor to understand what is causing the delay, assess whether an extension of settlement is appropriate, and advise on whether issuing a notice is the right strategic decision given your circumstances.</p>

      <p>In many cases, a brief extension of settlement is preferable to issuing a notice, particularly if the buyer's delay is temporary and they are genuinely committed to completing. Your solicitor can negotiate an extension with conditions, which is often a faster path to a successful settlement than formal enforcement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical implications for sellers who are also buying</h2>
      <p>If you are selling and buying simultaneously, a failed settlement on your sale is particularly disruptive. Your own purchase may be contingent on the sale proceeds, and your own settlement date may be immovable. In this situation, the ability to quickly issue a notice to complete and, if necessary, terminate and re-sell becomes critical.</p>

      <p>The best protection against this scenario is to have your solicitor build appropriate conditions into the contract from the outset, maintain close communication with your solicitor as settlement approaches, and have a contingency plan in place if the buyer encounters difficulties. Your agent should be keeping you informed about any signals from the buyer's side throughout the campaign and the pre-settlement period.</p>

